text:
On Saturday, Oct. 26, the Old Village Community Association honored five living legends who made major contributions to Laing School, its’ legacy and the community. Three of the honorees are retired teachers who inspired students at Laing and other Mount Pleasant area schools for generations.

The Laing School Tribute and Teacher Appreciation Day was held at the Miriam Moore Brown Community Center in the Old Village, named for the legendary principal who led Laing Elementary for 17 years.

The celebration featured two outstanding panel discussions that focused on the historic role of Laing School and on the importance of African American leaders as educators and role models in today’s schools.

The five honorees were:

• James E. Hilton, a retired science and algebra teacher who taught at Laing High School from 1955 to 1970 when the school was closed due to desegregation. He went on to teach at Moultrie and Wando High School;

• Sallie Horry Hilton, a Mount Pleasant native who taught business education at Lincoln High and Laing High School;

• Sue Meriwether Steed, a science teacher who taught at Laing, Moultrie and Wando. She began teaching at Laing after graduating from Winthrop in 1967 — the first African American student to earn a bachelor’s degree there;

• Dorothy E. Fludd, former Laing Alumni Association historian. She worked for 16 years with the New York Public Library, where she rose to become a Supervising Librarian. She returned home in 1984 and worked at the College of Charleston until she retired.

• Walter G. Brown, Jr., retired Charleston County Schools official and Mount Pleasant Historical Commission member. The first African American male to teach in a white school in Charleston, he retired in 1991 as the Director of Federal Programs for the Charleston County School District.

Panelists who spoke at the Tribute program included Mrs. Jeanette P. Singleton, retired Lincoln High School librarian and 1951 graduate of Laing High School; Professor Damon Fordham, historian and adjunct professor at The Citadel; Mount Pleasant Academy principal Kim Jackson; Dr. Micah Behrens, vice principal, Sand Hill Elementary School, Summerville and Karen Smalls-Horlback, retired career and technology educator, Sanders-Clyde Elementary and Wando High School. Author and poet Lornabelle Gethers served as moderator.
